WEBVTT

00:01.710 --> 00:03.542
<i>[theme music playing]</i>

00:09.760 --> 00:12.969
<i>(narrator) YOU'RE TRA VEL ING'
THROUGH ANOTHER DIMENSION.</i>

00:13.055 --> 00:15.888
<i>A DIMENSION NOT ONLY OF SIGHT
AND SOUND, BUT OF MIND,</i>

00:15.974 --> 00:17.760
<i>A JOURNEY INTO A WONDROUS LAND</i>

00:17.851 --> 00:20.092
<i>WHOSE BOUNDARIES
ARE THAT OF IMAGINATION.</i>

00:20.187 --> 00:23.475
<i>YOUR NEXT STOP,
THE TWILIGHT</i> ZONE.

00:41.291 --> 00:43.077
<i>[suspense music]</i>

02:02.122 --> 02:04.079
<i>[knock at door]</i>

02:20.349 --> 02:22.340
<i>[door opening
and then closing]</i>

02:25.604 --> 02:26.844
<i>(man)
SUZY!</i>

02:26.938 --> 02:28.975
DON'T TAKE THE LADY'S WATER.

02:29.066 --> 02:31.023
IT'S ALL RIGHT,
MR. SCHUSTER.

02:31.109 --> 02:32.270
<i>I'VE GOT PLENTY.</i>

02:32.361 --> 02:33.567
NOBODY'S GOT PLENTY.

02:33.654 --> 02:35.895
OH, MR. SCHUSTER, I THOUGHT

02:35.989 --> 02:37.730
<i>I HEARD
YOUR VOICE.</i>

02:37.824 --> 02:40.236
FOR THE LAST TIME, MRS.
BRONSON, VVE'RE LEAVING.

02:40.327 --> 02:43.160
DID YOU, UH,
DID YOU GET GAS?

02:43.246 --> 02:45.499
I GOT 12 GALLONS. I FIGURE
THAT OUGHT TO GET US

02:45.540 --> 02:46.871
AT LEAST
TO SYRACUSE.

02:46.958 --> 02:48.335
WHERE ARE YOU GOING?

02:48.418 --> 02:50.534
WE'RE TRYING
TO GET TO TORONTO.

02:50.629 --> 02:52.916
MR. SCHUSTER
HAS A COUSIN THERE.

02:53.006 --> 02:56.419
I'M NOT SURE IT'S WISE
YOU'RE DOING THIS.

02:56.510 --> 02:59.548
THE HIGHVVAYS ARE PACKED BUMPER
TO BUMPER, THE RADIO SAYS.

02:59.638 --> 03:02.505
AND WHAT WITH THE GAS
SHORTAGE AND EVERYTHING--

03:02.599 --> 03:03.885
I KNOW THAT,

03:03.975 --> 03:08.185
BUT WE'VE GOT
TO TRY ANYWAY.

03:08.271 --> 03:09.682
IT'S BEEN NICE
LIVING HERE.

03:09.773 --> 03:12.686
YOU'RE GOOD NEIGHBORS.

03:12.734 --> 03:15.692
LET'S GO, HONEY.

03:15.737 --> 03:18.900
<i>BYE.</i>

03:18.990 --> 03:21.027
GOOD LUCK.

03:23.787 --> 03:25.118
SAFE TRIP.

03:25.205 --> 03:26.661
<i>[door closes]</i>

03:28.834 --> 03:31.952
AND NOW WE ARE TWO.

03:32.045 --> 03:34.537
THEY WERE THE LAST?

03:34.631 --> 03:36.463
BUILDING'S EMPTY NOW.

03:36.550 --> 03:39.417
EXCEPT FOR YOU AND ME.

03:45.767 --> 03:48.145
WHAT HAPPENS NOW?

03:48.228 --> 03:49.309
I DON'T KNOW.

03:49.396 --> 03:51.012
I HEARD ON THE RADIO

03:51.106 --> 03:53.313
THAT THEY'RE ONLY GOING
TO TURN THE WATER ON

03:53.400 --> 03:54.856
AN HOUR A DAY FROM NOW ON.

03:54.943 --> 03:56.934
THEY SAID
THEY'D ANNOUNCE WHAT TIME.

03:57.028 --> 04:00.487
AREN'T YOU GOING TO LEAVE?

04:00.574 --> 04:03.612
NO.

04:03.702 --> 04:05.943
NO, I'M NOT GOING TO LEAVE.

04:06.037 --> 04:07.243
<i>[melancholy music]</i>

04:07.330 --> 04:10.493
YOU KNOW, MRS. BRONSON,

04:10.584 --> 04:14.999
I KEEP GETTING
THIS CRAZY THOUGHT.

04:17.007 --> 04:19.749
THIS CRAZY THOUGHT
THAT I'M GOING TO WAKE UP

04:19.801 --> 04:23.294
AND NONE OF THIS
WILL HAVE HAPPENED.

04:23.388 --> 04:26.506
I'LL WAKE UP
IN A COOL BED,

04:26.600 --> 04:29.342
IT'LL BE NIGHT OUTSIDE

04:29.436 --> 04:31.427
AND THERE'LL BE A WIND,

04:31.521 --> 04:34.479
BRANCHES RUSTLING,

04:34.566 --> 04:37.775
SHADOWS ON THE SIDEWALK,

04:37.861 --> 04:39.943
A MOON.

04:44.701 --> 04:48.285
TRAFFIC NOISES.

04:48.371 --> 04:49.827
AUTOMOBILES.

04:49.915 --> 04:51.576
<i>[suspense music]</i>

04:51.666 --> 04:53.452
<i>GARBAGE CANS.</i>

04:53.543 --> 04:56.956
MILK BOTTLES.

04:57.005 --> 04:58.746
AND VOICES.

04:58.840 --> 05:02.083
THERE WAS A SCIENTIST
ON THE RADIO THIS MORNING.

05:02.177 --> 05:04.885
HE SAID THAT IT'LL GET
A LOT HOTTER, MORE EACH DAY,

05:04.971 --> 05:07.303
NOW THAT WE'RE MOVING
SO CLOSE TO THE SUN.

05:07.390 --> 05:11.224
AND THAT'S WHY WE'RE--
[suspense music]

05:11.311 --> 05:13.143
THAT'S WHY WE'RE--

05:15.190 --> 05:17.807
THE WORD THAT MRS. BRONSON
IS UNABLE TO PUT

05:17.859 --> 05:20.942
INTO THE HOT, STILL,
SODDEN AIR IS "DOOMED"

05:21.029 --> 05:22.861
BECAUSE THE PEOPLE
YOU'VE JUST SEEN

05:22.948 --> 05:24.689
HAVE BEEN HANDED
A DEATH SENTENCE.

05:24.783 --> 05:26.273
ONE MONTH AGO, THE EARTH

05:26.368 --> 05:28.484
SUDDENLY CHANGED
ITS ELLIPTICAL ORBIT,

05:28.578 --> 05:30.239
AND BEGAN TO FOLLOW A PATH

05:30.330 --> 05:32.947
WHICH GRADUALLY,
MOMENT BY MOMENT, DAY BY DAY,

05:33.041 --> 05:35.328
TOOK IT CLOSER TO THE SUN.

05:35.418 --> 05:37.910
AND ALL OF MAN'S LITTLE
DEVICES TO STIR UP THE AIR

05:38.004 --> 05:39.836
ARE NOW NO LONGER LUXURIES.

05:39.923 --> 05:42.836
THEY HAPPEN TO BE PITIFUL
AND PANICKY KEYS TO SURVIVAL.

05:42.926 --> 05:45.258
THE TIME IS FIVE MINUTES
TO 12, MIDNIGHT.

05:45.345 --> 05:47.256
THERE IS NO MORE DARKNESS.

05:47.347 --> 05:50.885
THE PLACE IS NEW YORK CITY,
AND THIS IS THE EVE OF THE END

05:50.976 --> 05:53.968
BECAUSE EVEN AT MIDNIGHT,
IT'S HIGH NOON,

05:54.062 --> 05:55.894
THE HOTTEST DAY IN HISTORY,

05:55.981 --> 05:59.975
<i>AND YOU'RE ABOUT TO</i> SPEND <i>IT</i>
IN <i>THE TW/L/GHTZONE.</i>

06:02.779 --> 06:05.521
<i>[melancholy music]</i>

06:16.751 --> 06:19.743
<i>(Bronson)
NORMA, IS THAT YOU, HONEY?</i>

06:19.838 --> 06:20.999
YES, MRS. BRONSON.

06:26.803 --> 06:28.714
THE STORE WAS OPEN.

06:28.805 --> 06:30.466
WIDE OPEN.

06:30.557 --> 06:31.922
OH, I THINK

06:32.017 --> 06:33.678
THAT'S THE FIRST
TIME IN MY LIFE

06:33.768 --> 06:36.385
I WAS EVER SORRY
I WAS BORN A WOMAN.

06:36.479 --> 06:39.471
THIS IS ALL I VVAS
STRONG ENOUGH TO CARRY.

06:39.566 --> 06:43.150
THERE WEREN'T ANY
CLERKS AROUND.

06:43.236 --> 06:45.102
THANK YOU.

06:45.196 --> 06:47.574
JUST A HANDFUL
OF PEOPLE

06:47.616 --> 06:49.573
TAKING WHAT
THEY COULD GRAB.

06:49.659 --> 06:52.902
WELL, AT LEAST WE
WON'T STARVE ANYWAY.

06:52.996 --> 06:55.988
AND THERE ARE THREE CANS
OF FRUIT JUICE IN THERE.

06:56.082 --> 06:57.743
FRUIT JUICE?

06:57.792 --> 07:00.079
FRUIT JUICE?

07:00.128 --> 07:02.415
OH, NORMA, COULD WE
OPEN A CAN NOW?

07:02.505 --> 07:05.998
OH, OF COURSE WE
CAN OPEN A CAN NOW.

07:06.092 --> 07:09.835
OH, WHERE'S
THE CAN OPENER?

07:09.930 --> 07:12.137
OH, IN THE OTHER DRAWER.

07:20.982 --> 07:23.815
<i>[suspense music]</i>

07:23.902 --> 07:27.020
OH, I'M SORRY.

07:27.113 --> 07:30.902
I'M ACTING JUST LIKE
AN ANIMAL, AREN'T I?

07:30.992 --> 07:33.279
NO.

07:33.370 --> 07:34.986
NO, NO, JUST--

07:35.080 --> 07:38.289
JUST LIKE A FRIGHTENED
VVOMAN, THAT'S ALL.

07:38.375 --> 07:41.117
[chuckHng] YOU SHOULD
HAVE SEEN ME IN THE STORE

07:41.211 --> 07:43.498
RUNNING UP AND DOWN
THE AISLES,

07:43.588 --> 07:45.124
AND I MEAN RUNNING.

07:45.215 --> 07:48.424
KNOCKING THINGS OVER
AND GRABBING THINGS

07:48.510 --> 07:51.719
AND THROWING THEM AWAY
AND GRABBING AGAIN.

07:51.805 --> 07:53.170
AND AT THAT,
I THINK I WAS

07:53.264 --> 07:55.175
THE CALMEST PERSON
IN THE STORE.

07:55.266 --> 07:59.885
ONE WOMAN JUST STOOD IN THE
MIDDLE OF THE ROOM AND CRIED.

07:59.980 --> 08:02.187
SHE CRIED LIKE A BABY,

08:02.273 --> 08:04.981
PLEADING FOR SOMEONE
TO HELP HER.

08:05.068 --> 08:07.435
<i>(announcer over radio)
LADIES AND GENTLEMEN.</i>

08:07.529 --> 08:09.361
<i>THIS IS STATION WNYG</i>

08:09.447 --> 08:11.779
<i>COMING ON THE AIR
TO BRING YOU ESSENTIAL NEWS.</i>

08:11.866 --> 08:14.244
<i>FIRST, A BULLETIN
FROM THE POLICE DEPARTMENT.</i>

08:14.327 --> 08:16.193
<i>KEEP YOUR DOORS LOCKED.</i>

08:16.287 --> 08:18.870
<i>AND PREPARE TO PROTECT
YOURSELVES, IF NECESSARY,</i>

08:18.957 --> 08:20.493
<i>WITH ANY WEAPONS
YOU MAY HAVE.</i>

08:20.583 --> 08:22.324
<i>THE MAJORITY
OF THE POLICE FORCE</i>

08:22.419 --> 08:24.581
<i>HAS BEEN ASSIGNED
TO THE CROWDED HIGHWAYS.</i>

08:24.671 --> 08:26.253
<i>OUTSIDE THIS DESERTED CITY.</i>

08:26.339 --> 08:28.421
<i>AND CITIZENS
REMAINING IN NEW YORK</i>

08:28.508 --> 08:31.500
<i>MAY HAVE TO PROTECT THEMSELVES
FROM THE CRANKS AND LOOTERS</i>

08:31.594 --> 08:33.255
<i>KNOWN TO BE ROAMING
THE STREETS.</i>

08:33.346 --> 08:34.962
<i>FROM THE WEATHER BUREAU.</i>

08:35.056 --> 08:37.138
<i>THE TEMPERATURE
STOOD AT 110 DEGREES.</i>

08:37.225 --> 08:38.681
<i>AT 11:00 THIS MORNING.</i>

08:38.768 --> 08:40.850
<i>HUMIDITY, 91%.</i>

08:40.937 --> 08:43.850
<i>FORECAST FOR TOMORROW.</i>

08:43.940 --> 08:47.103
<i>FORECAST FOR TOMORROW--</i>

08:47.193 --> 08:49.981
<i>HOT. MORE OF THE SAME,
ONLY HOTTER.</i>

08:50.071 --> 08:52.278
<i>(man over radio)
STOP IT.</i>

08:52.365 --> 08:55.608
<i>(announcer) WHO ARE THEY KIDDING
WITH THIS WEATHER REPORT?</i>

08:55.702 --> 08:58.239
<i>TOMORROW YOU CAN FRY EGGS
ON SIDEWALKS,</i>

08:58.329 --> 09:00.286
<i>HEAT UP SOUP IN THE OCEAN,</i>

09:00.373 --> 09:02.990
<i>AND GET HELP FROM WANDERING
MANIACS IF YOU CHOOSE.</i>

09:03.084 --> 09:04.370
<i>WHAT DO YOU MEAN "PANIC"?</i>

09:04.461 --> 09:05.997
<i>WHO'S LEFT TO PANIC?</i>

09:06.087 --> 09:08.419
<i>[chuckles]
LADIES AND GENTLEMEN,</i>

09:08.506 --> 09:11.749
<i>I'M TOLD THAT MY DEPARTING FROM
THE SCRIPT MIGHT PANIC YOU AND--</i>

09:11.843 --> 09:13.754
<i>LET ME ALONE.
DO YOU HEAR ME?</i>

09:13.845 --> 09:16.382
<i>LET ME ALONE. LET GO OF ME.</i>

09:16.431 --> 09:18.547
TH ERE, <i>YOU--
[music playing over radio]</i>

09:18.641 --> 09:20.177
YOU SEE, MRS. BRONSON?

09:20.268 --> 09:23.056
YOU'RE NOT THE ONLY ONE
WHO'S FRIGHTENED.

09:27.108 --> 09:29.190
<i>THERE WE ARE.</i>

09:31.112 --> 09:33.820
<i>[liquid pouring]</i>

09:33.907 --> 09:36.148
<i>[music continues playing]</i>

09:39.662 --> 09:40.914
GO AHEAD, DRINK IT.

09:40.955 --> 09:42.571
IT'S GRAPEFRUIT JUICE.

09:42.665 --> 09:44.952
NO, I CAN'T. I CAN'T
LIVE OFF YOU LIKE THIS.

09:45.043 --> 09:46.579
YOU NEED IT
FOR YOURSELF.

09:46.669 --> 09:48.455
MRS. BRONSON,
WE'LL HAVE TO START

09:48.546 --> 09:51.254
LIVING OFF
EACH OTHER FROM NOW ON.

09:53.843 --> 09:55.345
<i>[clinks glasses]</i>

09:55.428 --> 09:57.260
HERE'S LOOKING AT YOU.

09:59.182 --> 10:02.095
<i>[music dies out]</i>

10:13.404 --> 10:15.782
CURRENT'S OFF AGAIN.

10:15.865 --> 10:19.779
IT STAYS ON A SHORTER
TIME EACH DAY.

10:19.828 --> 10:21.694
NORMA,

10:21.788 --> 10:24.701
WHAT IF IT SHUTS OFF AND,

10:24.791 --> 10:27.374
DOESN'T COME BACK ON AGAIN?

10:27.460 --> 10:29.201
<i>THIS PLACE
WOULD BE LIKE AN OVEN.</i>

10:29.295 --> 10:32.003
AS HOT AS IT IS,

10:32.090 --> 10:35.424
IT COULD BE
SO MUCH WORSE.

10:35.510 --> 10:38.377
<i>OH, NORMA, IT COULD
BE SO MUCH WORSE.</i>

10:38.471 --> 10:41.213
<i>[melancholy music]</i>

10:48.148 --> 10:49.764
NORMA.

10:54.445 --> 10:58.484
PLEASE PAINT
SOMETHING COOL TODAY.

11:02.453 --> 11:05.536
PAINT SOMETHING--

11:05.623 --> 11:07.705
PASTORAL.

11:10.170 --> 11:12.912
WITH A WATERFALL AND,

11:13.006 --> 11:16.374
TREES BENDING IN THE WIND.

11:18.678 --> 11:22.012
PLEASE PAINT SOMETHING COOL.

11:22.056 --> 11:25.469
DON'T PAINT THE SUN ANYMORE!

11:25.560 --> 11:29.269
DON'T PAINT THE SUN ANYMORE!

11:29.355 --> 11:30.937
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

11:31.024 --> 11:33.812
[sobbing]

11:43.328 --> 11:45.444
<i>[suspense music]</i>

11:45.538 --> 11:47.700
[panting]

12:07.852 --> 12:09.889
[sizzling, Norma gasps]

12:34.087 --> 12:36.545
MRS. BRONSON?

12:39.926 --> 12:41.837
MRS. BRONSON?

12:41.928 --> 12:43.418
<i>[Opening door]</i>

12:47.225 --> 12:49.182
YOU ALL RIGHT?

12:49.269 --> 12:51.761
YES, I'M ALL RIGHT.

12:51.854 --> 12:53.140
IT'S SO QUIET.

12:53.231 --> 12:55.973
I HAVEN'T
HEARD A SOUND.

12:56.067 --> 12:58.604
WHAT TIME IS IT?

12:58.695 --> 13:02.404
3:00 IN THE AFTERNOON.
[panting]

13:02.490 --> 13:04.606
DID YOU GET ANY SLEEP?

13:04.701 --> 13:06.157
I LAID DOWN AWHILE.

13:06.244 --> 13:07.609
<i>[soft thumping]</i>

13:07.704 --> 13:10.196
WHAT WAS THAT?

13:10.290 --> 13:12.452
SOUNDS LIKE
SOMETHING FELL.

13:12.542 --> 13:13.828
NO...

13:13.918 --> 13:15.784
IT WAS SOMEONE.

13:15.878 --> 13:17.789
DIDN'T YOU LOCK
THE ROOF DOOR?

13:17.880 --> 13:19.041
YES.

13:19.132 --> 13:20.122
NO, I--

13:20.216 --> 13:21.297
I DON'T KNOW, I--

13:21.342 --> 13:22.958
I DON'T REMEMBER.

13:23.052 --> 13:24.588
I THOUGHT I DID.

13:32.937 --> 13:35.144
<i>[footsteps approaching]</i>

13:39.736 --> 13:42.319
<i>[doorknob rattling]</i>

13:42.405 --> 13:45.193
<i>(man) HEY, SOMEBODY IN THERE?
COME ON OUT.</i>

13:47.410 --> 13:49.321
<i>COME ON OUT, BABY.</i>

13:49.412 --> 13:51.073
<i>COME ON OUT AND BE FRIENDLY.</i>

13:51.164 --> 13:54.156
<i>I AIN'T GOT ALL DAY.</i>

13:54.250 --> 13:56.582
<i>IF YOU DON'T COME OUT,
I'M GOING TO COME IN.</i>

14:03.634 --> 14:05.170
[cocks hammer]

14:05.261 --> 14:06.877
DID YOU HEAR THAT?

14:06.971 --> 14:08.177
THAT WAS A GUN.

14:08.264 --> 14:09.846
GET OUT OF HERE.

14:09.932 --> 14:12.765
DOWN THE STAIRS
AND OUT THE FRONT DOOR.

14:12.852 --> 14:15.844
LEAVE US ALONE.

14:15.897 --> 14:17.604
<i>(man)
OKAY, BABY.</i>

14:17.690 --> 14:22.526
<i>I NEVER ARGUE
WITH A LADY WITH A GUN.</i>

14:22.612 --> 14:24.444
<i>[footsteps walking away]</i>

14:30.203 --> 14:33.912
[sighs] OH, I'M SO
GLAD HE'S GONE.

14:33.998 --> 14:36.865
HE HASN'T COME OUT
THE FRONT DOOR YET.

14:36.918 --> 14:39.125
NO! NO!

14:39.212 --> 14:40.998
<i>[suspense music]</i>

14:55.895 --> 14:58.478
CRAZY DAM ES!

14:58.564 --> 15:01.932
IT'S TOO HOT TO PLAY GAMES.

15:02.026 --> 15:03.608
MUCH TOO HOT.

15:23.840 --> 15:25.922
<i>[glass shatters]</i>

15:51.367 --> 15:55.076
YOU DO THIS?

15:55.163 --> 15:57.370
YOU'RE GOOD.

15:57.457 --> 15:58.947
YOU PAINT REAL GOOD.

15:59.041 --> 16:01.783
<i>MY WIFE
USED TO PAINT.</i>

16:01.836 --> 16:03.372
PLEASE LEAVE
US ALONE.

16:03.463 --> 16:05.454
WE DIDN'T DO
YOU ANY HARM.

16:05.548 --> 16:06.913
PLEASE!

16:19.353 --> 16:21.390
[sighs]

16:21.481 --> 16:27.818
SHE WAS SO FRAGILE,
JUST-- JUST A LITTLE THING.

16:31.657 --> 16:35.651
SHE COULDN'T TAKE THIS HEAT.

16:35.703 --> 16:38.411
I TRIED TO KEEP HER COOL.

16:38.498 --> 16:41.411
BUT SHE COULDN'T
TAKE THE HEAT!

16:49.509 --> 16:52.718
BABY DIDN'T LIVE
MORE THAN AN HOUR.

16:56.015 --> 16:58.097
THEN SHE FOLLOWED HIM.

17:04.440 --> 17:08.684
I'M NOT A HOUSEBREAKER.

17:08.778 --> 17:10.314
I'M A DECENT MAN.

17:10.404 --> 17:13.613
<i>I SWEAR TO YOU,
I'M A DECENT MAN.</i>

17:13.699 --> 17:15.234
<i>I'VE BEEN WALKING AROUND</i>

17:15.326 --> 17:18.114
ALL, ALL DAY
TRYING TO FIND SOME WATER.

17:20.455 --> 17:22.071
[whimpering]

17:24.710 --> 17:26.747
I WOULDN'T HURT YOU.

17:29.173 --> 17:32.382
I WOULDN'T DO YOU ANY HARM.

17:34.136 --> 17:36.753
HONEST.

17:36.847 --> 17:38.929
PLEASE BELIEVE ME.

17:46.816 --> 17:48.853
PLEASE.

17:48.943 --> 17:51.025
PLEASE FORGIVE ME,
WOULD YOU?

17:51.112 --> 17:54.230
I'M JUST
OFF MY ROCKER.

18:00.454 --> 18:02.912
[panting]
PLEASE FORGIVE ME.

18:10.214 --> 18:11.921
WHY DOESN'T IT END?

18:11.966 --> 18:13.502
WHY DON'T WE JUST--

18:13.593 --> 18:16.255
JUST BURN UP?

18:22.143 --> 18:24.134
[sobbing]

18:45.666 --> 18:49.455
I PAINTED IT FOR
YOU LAST NIGHT.

18:49.545 --> 18:51.536
IT'S FOR YOU.

18:51.631 --> 18:56.626
OH, IT'S
BEAUTIFUL, NORMA.

18:56.719 --> 19:01.134
I'VE SEEN WATERFALLS
JUST LIKE THAT BEFORE.

19:01.223 --> 19:04.636
THERE'S, THERE'S ONE NEAR
ITHACA, NEW YORK.

19:04.685 --> 19:08.519
YES, IT'S
THE HIGHEST WATERFALL,

19:08.606 --> 19:12.725
THE HIGHEST WATERFALL
IN THIS PART OF THE COUNTRY.

19:12.818 --> 19:15.560
AND I LOVE THE SOUND OF IT.

19:15.655 --> 19:20.491
THAT WONDERFUL BLUE WATER
TUMBLING OVER THE ROCKS.

19:20.576 --> 19:25.195
THAT WONDERFUL,
COOL, CLEAR WATER.

19:25.289 --> 19:27.451
YOU HEAR IT, NORMA?
HEAR IT?

19:27.541 --> 19:30.408
<i>YOU DO HEAR IT,
NORMA, DON'T YOU?</i>

19:30.503 --> 19:32.460
<i>THAT WONDERFUL SOUND?</i>

19:32.546 --> 19:37.040
YOU KNOW, WE COULD--

19:37.134 --> 19:40.877
WE COULD SWIM
IN THAT WATERFALL.

19:40.971 --> 19:42.223
LET'S DO THAT.

19:42.306 --> 19:45.344
LET'S SWIM IN IT,
SHALL WE?

19:45.393 --> 19:49.261
I USED TO DO THAT WHEN I WAS
A LITTLE GIRL. [chuckHng]

